# Copy typography

Two conventions for visible copy and prose in this repo.

---

## Em dash → rightwards arrow

Do **not** use the **em dash** (`—`, U+2014). Use the **rightwards arrow** (`→`, U+2192) for the same visual break, lists, and “x then y” phrasing.

| Use | Do not use |
|-----|------------|
| `→` (U+2192) | `—` (U+2014) |

```tsx
// ❌
<p>We don&apos;t take a cut — hosts receive Interac.</p>

// ✅
<p>We don&apos;t take a cut → hosts receive Interac.</p>
```

**Hyphen** (`-`) and **en dash** (`–`) are out of scope unless you choose to normalize them separately.

---

## Ampersand → **and**

In **user-facing strings** (headlines, body copy, labels, button text, emails, aria where it’s sentence-like), write the word **and**. Do **not** use **`&`** as a substitute for “and”.

```tsx
// ❌
<span>Toronto & GTA</span>

// ✅
<span>Toronto and GTA</span>
```

### Do not “fix” these

Leave **`&`** as-is where it is syntax or escape machinery, not English “and”:

- JavaScript/logic: `&&`, `&` in bitwise ops
- URLs, query strings, form names
- HTML/XML **named character references**: `&amp;`, `&apos;`, `&quot;`, `&nbsp;`, numeric `&#…;`
- JSX **only when** the character `&` must appear literally and the framework/docs require an entity (prefer rewriting copy to **and** so entities stay rare)

When editing existing UI text, replace rhetorical **`&`** with **and** unless one of the exceptions applies.

When editing existing text, replace **`—`** with **`→`** unless the file is third-party, generated, or must stay verbatim.
